review_blob: Pours a clear deep honey color with a big foamy cream head. Very lively champagne bubbles keep the head supported. Aroma is light - doughy yeast and a bit floral but not very strong. Taste is immediately sweet - honey, ripe apples, plums, bananas foster - a hint of jasmine maybe. Not bitter at all the finish remains sweet with a touch of vanilla. The taste is much more powerful and complex than the aroma would suggest. Mouthfeel is smooth. This is an absolutely excellent brew and thoroughly exceeded my expectations!

Pours a cloudy light gold / dark yellow with a big white head that lingers. Aroma is on the lighter side - straw and light dough - not strong at all. Initial taste is slightly sour with flight floral notes - a diluted lemony essence throughout. Aftertaste is short and very slightly bitter. Palate is light with medium bubbles. Good, but a bit thin.

Pours a clear deep honey / golden amber with a big thick cream, very slightly peach head that lingers. Slightly sweet aroma with light bread, slight jasmine citrus scent - certainly a sweetness to the aroma. Taste is bigger than I expected. Immediate bread, followed by a good amount of sweet - like ripe mellon dipped into vanilla yogurt. Cant understate the sugar here - its not unlike a deep chardonnay. Mouthfeel is thin given the sweetness, which is a nice contrast. Very light aftertaste. Very good, very sugar forward.

Pours a hazy orange maize with a frothy white head that lingers. Banana and slight bubblegum. Morning bun with citrus zest. Taste upfront is blood orange and dried apricot - a citrusy sweetness. Middle is white bread crust that gives way to a floral and slightly bitter aftertaste that lingers. Mouthfeel is light but slightly slick with lively bubbles. A very good Tripel that I find to be such more complex and drinkable than the Dubbel. Fantastic.

Pours a clear reddish orange gold with a big eggshell bubble-bath head that supports itself and lingers in a tulip glass. Aroma is dough, yeast and straw with little hints of citrus. Taste is bread pudding and very thick french toast. Vanilla, banana and spring water. Maybe even a little melon. Undertones of bread crust and some nearly imperceptible hints of darker fruit. Palate is crisp. Finish is clean and leaves very slight and pleasant bitterness behind. Outstanding.

Pours deep dark opaque brown with an almost soda-like dark tan head - almost looked like a thick coca-cola. Dissipated over a couple minutes leaving minimal lacing. Aroma is sweetened coffee, dark chocolate, hints of caramel and roasted nuts and maybe even a little leather. Taste is dark yet sweet fruits supported by coffee and caramel chocolate undertones. Theres an immediate bitterness that lingers to a black coffee aftertaste. The palate is creamy and a bit viscous but is cut nicely by lively carbonation. Its a big beer, great for sipping. Only one is needed. I like this and appreciate it as a great beer, but personally dont love it.

Pours a thick maple chestnut with a big thick tanned head that continues to stand. Aroma is brandied cherries, smoke, teriyaki and spice. Malty overtones. Flavor is immediately dark. Sweetened coffee, brandied cherries, spice cake, little bit of cloves and cinnamon. Mouthfeel is slightly sticky with tiny soft bubbles. Finish lingers and is brown bread. Obviously a very good and very complex one - somehow leaves me wanting a little bit more but perhaps thats just my expectations. Still an excellent excellent beer.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Pours a cloudy haystack blonde with a soapy head that lingers and clings to the glass. The aroma packs a punch! Doughy, yeasty then pears, apples, pineapple juice, maybe even a touch of bubblegum? The taste is powerful, high assertive notes of passion fruit, then to dough then supported by pleasantly bitter breadcrust undertones, maybe a well-done pancake. Really hits the full octave. The hoppy aftertaste remains on the tongue but is in no-way overpowering. Mouthfeel is right down the middle of the fairway and not too thick, which would have been a little much. Overall this is an excellent, excellent and very well thought out beer - not surprising from the Lost Abbey folks.

Pours a cloudy caramel color with an eggshell frothy white head that takes its time to dissipate and laces the glass well. Aroma is yeasty caramel with a very faint orange blossom, jasmine. Feels thick on the mouth with a very soft creamy carbonation - very near nitro. A slightly sour wateriness at first that comes around almost immediately to malt. Some very very very faint cherry spice near the end and a clean finish with just a small touch of bitterness on the tongue. I keep coming back to a faint lemon tea. Its good, but its not as flavorful as its mouthfeel suggests. I keep wanting a bit more flavor, and that seems like it might be intentional. With the soft carbonation and light flavor I could certainly settle into a few of these, but probably only if all other options were limited.

So the score of this beer doesnt do justice to the fact that on a sunny day outside I could and would drink copious amounts of this stuff. Pours a clear gold with a thick white head. Aroma is malty sweet. Flavor was malt that turned into a bit of a canned mandarin orange undertone with a slight bitter finish on the back-end with minimal aftertaste. I didnt find it to be anything terribly special but found it very drinkable. Bottom line, enjoyable.

Pours a dark honey color with the cloudy characteristic of a belgian. Leaves a full what head that leaves more lacing than most. Immediate honey on the nose - if not honey than a sauternes-style sweetness. Taste is an instant sweetness that transitions to a bit of fresh water than to a light sourness and a slightly bitter finish. Notes of honey and dessert wine (again, sauternes) that then fades into a tart lemon/plum (if that makes any sense. I actually find the initial rich sweetness that fades into a light tartness highly appealing. Mouthfeel is slightly viscous, but not sticky with a soft carbonation. This surprised me to the upside in a lot of ways. Sure, its not as complex as others for its category, but I find it delicious.

Pours a cloudy toasted orange color with a small, light yellow head that quickly dissipates. On the nose is citrus/orange lemon cake. Taste is immediately tart but not ought right sour. A big squeeze of lemon onto yellow cake - other citrus notes and a faint background of apricots. Hints of golden brown toast on the back end and the harness lingers through the finish. Mouthfeel is much lighter than I expected and not sticky at all which I think is a feat given its tartness. Tiny and lively carbonation. This is fantastic and a great summer day drinker which I didnt expect given red wine barrel aging.

It pours like a 16 ounce espresso, with a brown head that dissipates fairly quickly dissipated. Small fizzy bubbles on the tongue. Actually a little brighter than I expected. Coffee-chocolate, currant, cherry honey and cocoa. Aftertaste is sweet and doesnt linger, which I see as a plus. This is way more complex than the blunt force object I anticipated. A huge beer, but also hugely drinkable! Warmth in the back of the throat remains. Very well done!

This was a two year old bottle that had been in the back of my fridge.

Pours a clear amber with sediment. Medium eggshell head that lingers a couple minutes. Sent is very much hops with malt undertones. Leans fruity. Mouthfeel is slightly chewy but not so much so to not be refreshing. Medium carbonation. Taste is almost the inverse of the smell. I got malt with hoppy undertones. Aside from the not overbearing shroud of malt is a very pleasant floral taste: rose and jasmine. Maybe even a hint of something tropical like mango. Importantly though this isnt too sweet, and the finish is almost a non sticky carmel chocolate (rolos?!) with a very faint burnt coffee. I very much like this beer and to my tastes its underrated a bit here.
beer_name: Castelain St. Amand French Country Ale

review_blob: Pours a medium orange cloudy Carmel. Big light eggshell head that lingers. Aroma is immediate yeasty dough with some faint light fruit in the background. Alcohol smell is slightly apparent. Nothing spectacular. Mouthfeel is light yet satisfying with a soft but not unlively carbonation. The sweetness of yeasty light fruit is immediate and much stronger than the aroma lets on. Apples both sweet and tart and apricot for sure. The yeast is smooth and pleasant. Its actually making me a bit hungry. The immediate hit of fruit and yeast upfront gives way to a slight apple aftertaste that fades away. Drinking this one day after the hops of Lost Abbey Gift of the Magi had its way with my taste buds. Highly refreshing and makes me look forward to spring and summer. Im not sure that I expected something this light in a quadruple but Im enjoying this a lot.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob:
Cloudy burnt orange color.
Pours cloudy, burnt orange with a robust dark eggshell head. Nose is immediately malty and as the head slowly dissipates leaving no lacing, dried apricots emerge. A mix of light fruit and darker fruit are existent yet shrouded in the fog of malt. Yeasty undertones are detectable yet not prevalent. Mouth feel is viscous and chewy yet is cut by a relatively forceful carbonation. Initial hops not necessarily apparent on the nose hit the palate hard. The dried fruits apparent in the scent follow through behind the initial onslaught of hops. The maltiness of the nose does not necessarily carry through to the mouth. After taste is surprisingly light. A sticky hop onslaught.
beer_name: Lost Abbey Gift of the Magi

review_blob: Pours a dark apple cider with an eggshell off white creamy head that lingers. Aroma is fairly light, bread, yeast and banana. Mouthfeel is pleasantly lighter than I expected, with small but lively carbonation. Taste is on the sweeter side: sweet rolls, apple, banana with a slight honey undertone. Aftertaste is very light and pleasantly sweet. Very high drink ability here.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Pours a creamy light toffee brown with an unremarkable head that dissipates after a couple minutes. Smell is toasted with dark dried fruits. Light, small carbonation creates a light creamy mouthfeel. Taste follows through the smell, toasted nuts, chocolate, dried dark fruits and a slight apple astringency to balance things out. As it warmed a distinct butterscotch emerged in the background. Leaves a toasty aftertaste but without leaving your tastebuds in ruins. For the complexity, its very drinkable. Great beer.
UPDATED: MAR 2, 2016

Pours a dark deep brown amber that almost resembles coca-cola in appearance (a good thing!)  Has a ver large tan head that slowly descends into a 1/4 inch thick head that leaves ample lacing.  The aroma really struck me.  It is incredibly malty smelling, almost to the point of triggering an appatite in me.  This might sound really absured, but it almost has a hash (as in the food) smell.  Very different and very appealing.  Mouthfeel is slightly viscous, but not sticky at all.  Taste is excellent.  Dark fruits and maple nut upfront, with a maltyness that lighty wraps the whole flavor and lingers in what is a very gentle aftertaste.  This beer is complex, balanced, and not overpowering a all.  You can tell a lot of thought went into this one, and it is thouroughly drinkable and enjoyable.  Excellent.

One of the few Unibroue beers Ive yet to have - and Ive gotta say, its weel worth the wait.  Pours a saturnes gold color that is very slightly cloudy.  The head pours large, but is not terribly dense and dissipates quickly to leave a ring but no lacing.  Aroma is decidedly fruity, but not overwealmingly so.  Id say almost a fruit cocktail of sorts.  Im getting peaches, pears, apple, and a citurs layer.  Through it all is the obligatory Unibroue yeast, but not nearly as strong as usual (Ephemere has more yeast)!  Mouthfeel is consistent moderate carbonation.  Not too thick, not too thin.  The taste is pretty much what you get from the aroma, with a well balanced yeast and fruit upfront and slowly fading away into a fruit aftertaste.  Outstanding beer, and very, very drinkable!

Interesting to say the least.  Pours a transparent apple juice gold with a small, thin white head.  Because of the apple expectation, I went in with  the expectation of a cider-like aroma.  I was suprised (I know I shouldnt have been) when I receieved almost equal amounts of apple and yeast (should have expected this from a Unibroue beer).  Maybe the aroma can be chalked up to "dusty apple."  The palate is very soft, with carbonation nearing after-thought status.  The initial sour apple flavor is unmistakeable, but this beer has, as the aroma suggested, and almost equal wallop of yeast.  What is dissapointing to me, however, is how thin this beer is and how quickly the flavor dissipates.  What begins a musky apple quickly slides off into a sour water, as if someone put a tea bag in water for ten seconds, only leaving the slightest essence of flavor.  I think this is a decent beer to have tried at least, and its saving grace might be that it probably serves as a nice complement to a humid summer day.  Other than that, theres really not the complexity that I was hoping for or expecting.

Okay so lets begin with the fact tha this is only a 6 month old bottle.  Aroma struck me as Hefeweizen, but as others have noted, has that signature "Unibroue" yeast aroma.  In sum the aroma was yeasty and doughy with maybe a very small hint of citrus.  The pour itself was a bright, cloudy apricot with a big white foam head that eventually collapsed into a nice layer that left a decent lacing.  The mouth feel was light with a small, lively carbonation.  Taste was a beginning of a thin round of yeaty dough that quickly gives way to a prevailing sugary orange citrus.  Its loaded with bananas with a sweetness rich enough to lead to hints of brown sugar.  The finish goes back to doughy without much of an aftertaste.  The fruitiness and sweetness develops in intensity and complexity as it warms; which isnt much of a suprise.  Look, this stuff is good, but for a fiftheenth anniversary, I would expect something a little more inspired.  THAT BEING SAID, Im going to go get about 4 more of these things and drink em at 6 month intervals.

Pours a very dark, deep red with a lively tan head that dissipates fairly quickly.  Aroma is very assertive, loaded with dark fruits.  Flavor is phenomenal, with an immediate smoke and roasted coffee flavors that is mellowed by dark fruit undertones  cherry and plum  and even a little citrus.  Might sound odd, but even a little beef jerky, but in a good way!  The fruit flavors become more prevalent towards the finish, which has a gentle spicy bite to it.  Finish leaves a roasted smoke on the palate.  Palate is fairly thin with a lively carbonation.  Overall I think this is an excellent brew that is very, very drinkable.

Pours a thick black with traces of dark, dark brown.  Like filling the glass with motor oil.  Has a medium sized dark tan head that lingers into a film, leaving minimal lacing.  Aroma is hops, coffee and chocolate.  Initial bitterness, with the obligatory coffee and chocolate.  Then is when it takes a great turn towards dark fruit, maybe dark cherry and plum, but all thrown into chocolate.  Hops are incredibly prevelent, and really work to add a lot of depth to the roast malt.  The carbonation is lively, and  dont get me wrong, this is a thick beer  makes it pleasantly lighter than it looks.  Overall, a very intellegent and intricate stout.  Very impressive, and another victory for Victory.

Pours a very dark, almost black amber  at first glance it looks like a stout with a good sized tan head that dissipates into nothing rather quickly.  What immediately jumped out at me was the very lively carbonation that was audible from a few feet away.  The aroma, while not overpowering is hints of chocolate and light fruit. Taste is VERY distinctive, immediately I thought oak and more oak.  This really tastes like a carbonated port with hints of grape and a well placed spicyness..  The carbonation is so intense as to be annoying, as the flavor is much more reminicent of port than beer.  Okay as it warms, the carbonation dissipates a bit.  Really, Im shocked more ratebeer deScriptions dont mention port and oak.  Also, a well aged burgandy.  Really one hell of an impressive and unique tasting beer.  Mouthfeel is light, and as I said, lively carbonation.  Ive gotta say, as a wine fan, I love this stuff.
UPDATED: MAR 5, 2016

Pours a dark brown cloudy amber with an enourmous light tan head.  Aroma is very yeasty with grass much like other Unibroue brews.  Im actually finding the taste fairly bland and watery, with a hint of green apple, and some citrus.  Im thinking it may be this bottle, as Ive had this beer a few times in the past and have found it much more complex than this bottle is presenting itself as.  Really, what is constantly coming up in my mind is watery.  Mouthfeel is thin.  Ive gotta admit Im dissapointed in this one.  Its stull good, but not all I think it can be or usually is.  For now, Im going to chalk it up to the bottle, Ill go back and re-rate with another later.

Pours a thick, jet black that blocks out any semblance of light.  The head, while hard to coax out, is dark tan, and quickly dissipates.  An intimidating looking beer.  Aroma is chocolate and burnt grains, coffee, and nuts.  The taste is amazingly complex.  I went into my first step thinking this is going to be a kick your ass knock down drag out stout, and found myself shocked at the amazing array of flavors.  If you have bud light on one end of the spectrum, and port on the other, this is a close cousin to the latter.  Chocolate is powerful and right up front, with very sugary dark fruits, tons of raisins, backed by plums, cherry, and molassis.  In the background is roasted nuts and coffee, but playing a distinct second fiddle to the sweeter flavors.  Port shines through with a spiciness of a good abt/quadrupel.  Lets not kid around; this is dessert.  The finish is warmed by the alcohol as as the sweetness lingers.  The palate?  Ive had thinner oatmeal.  The carbonation is soft but assertive.  Okay, Ill admit I was shocked that this was ten bucks for twelve ounces, but now I get it.  Worth it completely.  I think Ive gained five pounds.  Amazing after dinner/for dinner drink.  A good one to knock the socks off of wine snob friends that pay no respect to the mighty grain.

Pours a clear dark red mahogany with an enormous foamy tan head.  The lacing sticks to the glass and clings for dear life.  Tons of fruit flavor.  Aroma is dark fruit, but not overpowering.  As for taste:  I immediately thought cherry vanilla backed by a variety of citrus.  Maybe even hints of chocolate, and certainly maple syrup.  The sweetness is by no means overpowering and is well balanced by hops, which lend to a pleasant bitterness.  Finish is hops with a hint of those fruit candies that come in the round tins (your grandmother probably had them).  Palate is certainly a bit syrupy, and itll stick to your lips a little bit after its done.  A very smooth, small, soft, and gentle carbonation.  Overall this is a very good, very well balanced barleywine.

Pours a fairly clear gold orange with red accents with a large white head that lingers.  The lacing is all encompassing.  Aroma is powerful hops with flowers and citrus.  This is a HUGE beer.  Hops upon hops.  After what is a pillage of bitterness, the sky clears to reveal an incredible complexity of floral, citrus and maybe even candy flavors.  Oh theres malt alright  for those that find their way through the hops.  Believe it or not, its really well balanced.  More flavors.  Grapefruit.  Pine.  The alcohol lets you know its there, but pleasantly so.  This isnt a thick beer at all, but it really wants to be chewed.  Great for sipping.  Again, this is a powerful one, and will be the only beer youll taste for the rest of the day, so make it your last.  Even for someone whos not a huge IPA fan, this is a great beer.
UPDATED: FEB 9, 2014

Pours a hazy golden straw blonde.  Big foamy white head that stays put,  Yeasty aroma.  Initial yeasty and mildly malty flavor has the best transition to citrus, white grape, and other fruit  Ive had so far.  The taste immediately beyond the intitial yeast is wonderfully remeniscnet of a well aged burgandy -thanks for that, Burt  but rather than going into a deep red wine flavor it falls into the lively citrus and other light fruit with a gentle spicyness.  The flavor balance between strong and sweet that is highlighted by that distinctly aged burgandy transition between them creates one of the best balanced beers Ive head that actually has a very distinct flavor movement.  Now, Im drinking this about seven hours after a bomber of bastard (which pillaged my tastebuds for at least four hours) and it may be one of the most refreshing follow-ups ever.  Palate is smooth and lightly silky with lively, gentle bubbles.  Great brew!
UPDATED: FEB 27, 2007

Pours a thick milk chocolate brown with the slightest tint of burnt orange with a two to three finger spongy head that slowly dissipates and leaves a thick lacing.  Aroma is chocolate, raisin, fig, and bread pudding.  Taste is unbelievably complex  Raisin, fig, rum, bread, bread pudding, port  spicy - it keeps changing! Apple cider, some sort of dark fruit jam as it finishes with the perfect bitterness.  There is an incredible amount of stuff going on here, Im sure I didnt capture it all.  Palate is slightly creamy but very fresh, with a lively carbonation that really brings out the spicy flavors and seems to foam up as you work it around your mouth.  As a somewhat of a novice, this is the best beer Ive ever had.

Pours a deep burnt ruby amber with a large very frothy tan head that lingers.  Lacing is full and plentiful.  An orange ring arounf the top when the head finally dissipates.  This stuff sticks!  Aroma is strong, with grapefruit, other citrus, spice, and pine.  Flavor hits with a very obvious and pronounced grapefruit followed by sweeter citrus to round out a near perfect spectrum of bittersweetness.  Pine comes through to introduce oak and other woody flavors.  Has a decent amount of spicy bite to it as well.  Just a hint of vanilla that may be a testament to the surprisingly creamy palate.  Bitter pine-y aftertaste lasts a good amount of time Moderate small bubble carbonation.  This stuff is phenomenal  Definitely going to take the other five and let em age...hope I can resist!

Poured a cloudy, dark, light milk chocolate brown with a slight red tinge. A frothy tan head dissipates quickly into a translucent tan film. Aroma is spicy with hints of fruit and chocolate.  Palate is light cream with a mild, soft carbonation.  Taste is incredibly complex, dark chocolate, dark cherry and other dark fruits such as raisin.  The sweetness is pervasive  maybe a hint of caramel.  Alcohol is present, but comes across as red wine.  There is a nuttiness, but it only emerges for a second out of the fruit.  Spiciness includes cloves.  I could contemplate this one for a hell of a long time.  An incredible beer.  As complex as Ive ever had.

Had this one in Belize City, Belize.  It wasnt anything terribly special, but for a big national brew it beats the hell out of anything the US can come up with.  Aroma was very malty and grainy.  Taste was a pleasantly surprising fruit  subtle pineapple and banana, with plenty of grains and a hoppy finish.  Carbonation is what you would expect from a cheap beer.  Overall though, I enjoyed this one.  About seven times.  It really helps actually being in Belize when you have this one.

Pours a cloudy, nutty, iced tea brown.  Tan, two finger frothy head diminishes to a tan film with pronounced center as carbonation comes up from the center in the Trappist glass.  A medium palate with a slightly oily texture with lively small carbonation.  Leaves a very full, even lacing that lingers for a moment before descending the walls of the glass.  Aroma is a slightly sweet spice with a nutty background  not terribly strong. Initial banana sweetness was a surprise, then goes into a profound choco-nut, autumn spices and clove linger to the finish.  Maybe cassis as well?  Has a very pleasant mild spicy bite to it. Barely a trace of bitterness to add balance.  A truly great beer.  Loved every second of it.

Pours pitch black with a good sized, foamy tan head with a great lacing. This is a downright burly looking beer. Aroma is burnt nutty malt.  The flavors hit hard: Choco-nut, with slightly burnt chocolate malt which keeps it from being too sweet.  The dark chocolate really comes through brilliantly  never too sweet, yet assertively present.  Malty.  Chocolate.  Burnt nuts.  Brilliant.  The finish is bitter enough to balance everything out, and the aftertaste is a slowly lingering bakers chocolate.  Palate is rich and syrupy, but really not exceeding so at all.  A phenomenal brew!

Pours a burnt orange amber with a frothy barely off white head that lingers for the duration of the beer.  When it does finally descend it leaves a solid lacing.  Aroma is wheat and a hoppy citrus with a distinct citrus scent.  Initial flavor is nutty and sweetly peppery, then transitions right into fruity citrus flavors including green apple, raisin, and an array of other subtle dark fruits.  Underlying honey and understated port round things out.  Finished long with fruit (mostly raisin and green apple) and a mild bitterness.  Palate is a moderately thick oil with a lively small carbonation not unlike champaign.  Overall a fantastic complex tripel.  Really enjoyed this one!

Pours pink with a hint of orange.  Aroma is bread and berries.  Head is a moderate white bubbly foam that quickly dissipates into a small white ring.  Minimal lacing.  Taste is an underwhelming wheat beer with watered down raspberries.  Where other flavors would usually present, all you get is water.  All in all, it tastes like an under-steeped tea.  Bummer.  Finishes with a medium bitterness.  Palate is watery with medium carbonation.  A swing and a miss for Abita.

Pours a slightly burnt orange with a very large bubbly white head mostly diminishing leaving a white froth with moderate lacing.  Yeasty aroma is confident but not overpowering. Dough, grain, cereal, and spicy citrus.  A light creamy palate with lively  but not too aggressive  carbonation.  Taste:  definite citrus (mostly orange) and banana, hints of pineapple. Overall a pleasant sweetness well balanced by a wheat undertone.  Sweetness become more prominent as it warms.  Nice hops on the finish, alcohol is detectable    An absolutely wonderful beer in virtually every aspect.

Pours a hazy golden straw, with a good amount of particles. A large, frothy white head slowly reduced to a thick, solid white film that left a great lacing.  Strong aroma of straw, cooked corn, and a slight mold  a dry haystack on a warm summer day.  The aroma is clearly one of the foremost aspects of drinking this beer and one gets the feeling you either love it or hate it.  Soft yet clearly present carbonation with a slightly oily palate. A very appealing and substantive taste of corn and muted clove, undercooked bread, long lasting wheat finish.  Almost no bitterness.  An ideal relaxing and refreshing beer for a hot summer day.  Overall a very well made beer.  Cant go wrong here at all.

Poured mahogany, with very little head,  Aroma very hard to pick up, especially in a bar.  Initial nutty smoked grains - but not as nutty has many nut browns - followed by lots of sweet, caramel malts, maybe some dark fruits as well.  Palate was thin with a fairly lazy carbonation.  A rather sweet beer, could easily put down a lot in a short amount of time.  Overall, an upbeat beer that will be one of the better things on tap at most bars.

A good, solid beer.  Dark color, medium body.  Khaki head quickly dissapates to a film, but leaves a nice lacing. Suprisingly light silky palate, and very smooth.  Definitely chocolate, toffee, caramel, and maybe even a little dark cherry.  Nothing spectacular, but a good drinking beer to come back to.

Pours a peach/deep pink color with a fine white head that reduces to a nice lacing.  Very light on the palate with an initial wheat and light yeasty flavor - lets you know that this is, indeed, a beer - followed  by distinct, yet mildly watery fruit flavors.  Predominantly currant, but also a bitter apple, cherry, and peach.  Finishes with an quick, mild bitterness. Drinks like a sparkling cider.

Pours black  a very deep red  with a medium tan head that fairly quickly to a tan film.  Decent lacing.  Initial flavor is nuts and coffee lending to an overall roasted flavor.  The remaining flavors I found to be present at first, but became became more prevelant as the beer warmed:  Hints of chocolate turns over to caramel then understated hoppy citrus brings sweetness. Also a distinct underlying bitterness throughout .  Drinks smooth yet crisp and not too heavy.  Found the soba to be undetectable, but Im not sure I knew what to look for .  A good drinkable beer overall, but nothing terribly special.
beer_name: Rogue Morimoto Black Obi Soba Ale
